body:
`LowerClasses` fails to lower external modules which have properties when the external modules have the same defname. Consider the following:

``` mlir
firrtl.circuit "Foo" {
  firrtl.extmodule @Bar_1<WIDTH: ui32 = 1>(
    in a: !firrtl.integer,
    in b: !firrtl.uint<1>
  ) attributes {defname = "Bar"}
  firrtl.extmodule @Bar_2<WIDTH: ui32 = 2>(
    in a: !firrtl.integer,
    in b: !firrtl.uint<2>
  ) attributes {defname = "Bar"}
  firrtl.module @Foo() {
    %bar_1_a, %bar_1_b = firrtl.instance bar_1 @Bar_1(
      in a: !firrtl.integer,
      in b: !firrtl.uint<1>
    )
    %bar_2_a, %bar_2_b = firrtl.instance bar_2 @Bar_2(
      in a: !firrtl.integer,
      in b: !firrtl.uint<2>
    )
    %0 = firrtl.integer 0
    firrtl.propassign %bar_1_a, %0 : !firrtl.integer
    firrtl.propassign %bar_2_a, %0 : !firrtl.integer
  }
}
```

This can be compiled with:

``` console
# circt-opt -pass-pipeline='builtin.module(firrtl.circuit(firrtl-lower-classes))' Foo.mlir
Foo.mlir:6:3: error: redefinition of symbol named 'Bar_Class'
  firrtl.extmodule @Bar_2<WIDTH: ui32 = 2>(
  ^
Foo.mlir:6:3: note: see current operation: 
"om.class.extern"() <{fieldNames = [], fieldTypes = {}, formalParamNames = ["basepath", "a"], sym_name = "Bar_Class"}> ({
^bb0(%arg0: !om.basepath, %arg1: !om.integer):
}) : () -> ()
Foo.mlir:2:3: note: see existing symbol definition here
  firrtl.extmodule @Bar_1<WIDTH: ui32 = 1>(
  ^
```

I think the right thing to do here is to only create one class for each external module with that defname.

Note: the root issue here is a representational one where external modules with parameters are not actually modules, but instantiations of specific parametric modules. A much larger refactor to change this representation so that there was exactly one module for `Bar` that had parameters bound at the instantiation site and a way to represent the fact that the parameters affect the widths of ports would fix this. E.g.:

``` mlir
firrtl.circuit "Foo" {
  firrtl.extmodule @Bar<WIDTH: ui32>(
    in a: !firrtl.integer,
    in b: !firrtl.uint<WIDTH>
  )
  firrtl.module @Foo() {
    %bar_1_a, %bar_1_b = firrtl.instance bar_1 @Bar<1>(
      in a: !firrtl.integer,
      in b: !firrtl.uint<1>
    )
    %bar_2_a, %bar_2_b = firrtl.instance bar_2 @Bar<2>(
      in a: !firrtl.integer,
      in b: !firrtl.uint<2>
    )
    %0 = firrtl.integer 0
    firrtl.propassign %bar_1_a, %0 : !firrtl.integer
    firrtl.propassign %bar_2_a, %0 : !firrtl.integer
  }
}
```
